{"id":"0807.1984","submitter":"Julian Sienkiewicz","authors":"Julian Sienkiewicz, Janusz A. Holyst","title":"Nonequilibrium phase transition due to social group isolation","comments":"5 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 80, 036103 (2009)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.80.036103","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph physics.comp-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We introduce a simple model of a growing system with $m$ competing\ncommunities. The model corresponds to the phenomenon of defeats suffered by\nsocial groups living in isolation. A nonequilibrium phase transition is\nobserved when at critical time $t_c$ the first isolated cluster occurs. In the\none-dimensional system the volume of the new phase, i.e. the number of the\nisolated individuals, increases with time as $Z \\sim t^3$. For a large number\nof possible communities the critical density of filled space equals to $\\rho_c\n= (m/N)^{1/3}$ where $N$ is the system size. A similar transition is observed\nfor Erd\\H{o}s-R\\'{e}nyi random graphs and Barab\\'{a}si-Albert scale-free\nnetworks. Analytic results are in agreement with numerical simulations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 12 Jul 2008 15:50:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 25 Feb 2009 14:52:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-03-15"}
